User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 21, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 42 responses, 15 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 36% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

Based on the survey responses, the most common research area is Cognitive Neuroscience, with many respondents specifically mentioning this field or sub-fields like cognitive neuroscience of language, music cognition, and cognitive neuroscience of music. Other prominent areas include:

  • Neurology/Neuroscience: Including research on neurodegenerative diseases, brain injury, multiple sclerosis, and general neuroscience.
  • Mental Health: Covering a broad range, including mental disorders, psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, and disorders like anorexia nervosa.
  • Aging and Dementia: A significant focus, with interests in healthy aging, dementia, cerebrovascular disease, and age-related cognitive decline.
  • Brain and Cognition: Research involving areas such as attention, decision-making, language processing, learning, brain connectivity, etc.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, increased access to MRI would significantly expand and improve research in several key areas:

  • Neurological and Psychiatric Disorders: MRI is crucial for understanding brain changes and function in conditions like ADHD (particularly in women), Alzheimer’s, Lewy body dementia, multiple sclerosis (MS), lupus nephritis, and other psychiatric disorders. It allows for identification of biomarkers, tracking disease progression, and assessing the effectiveness of interventions (e.g., non-invasive brain stimulation, HRT).
  • Cognitive Neuroscience: MRI is essential for studying cognitive functions like memory, attention, language (bilingualism), and executive functions. It helps to delineate brain areas involved in these processes and understand how they change across the lifespan and with age-related changes.
  • Basic Neuroscience: MRI facilitates the investigation of fundamental neural mechanisms, including those underlying sexual function, partner attraction, decision-making, pain perception, and the effects of interventions on brain anatomy and activity. It also allows for the study of brain networks and their connectivity.
  • Methodological Advancement: Increased access would enable method development in MRI techniques and the validation of findings across populations, as well as for the study of the effects of interventions on brain anatomy, plasticity and activity.
  • Increased Research Capacity and Collaboration: Better access, especially with trained scientific management, would increase study sample sizes, facilitate multi-center collaborations (both nationally and internationally), make studies more feasible for remote populations, and support more student research (master’s and PhD theses).
  • Grant Funding: Having access to MRI and building neuroimaging experience would improve the likelihood of securing grant funding for research projects.
  • Novel Research Areas: Researchers could expand into new areas, such as studying the neural correlates of interacting with artificial agents, geohazard in geological archives, and decoding visual representations.
  • Combining with Other Methods: MRI would complement existing research using techniques like EEG, EMG, and non-invasive brain stimulation, providing spatial information and neural network perspectives.
  • Clinical Relevance: MRI provides clinically relevant information for decision-making and developing novel algorithms for disease monitoring and treatment.

In summary, lack of access to MRI is a major impediment to many researchers. Improved access would enable a wider range of studies, increase research quality, facilitate collaboration, and ultimately advance our understanding of the brain and its role in health and disease.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Survey respondents highlighted several key areas for improvement in MRI research. A major theme was enhancing access and resources, with suggestions including establishing a dedicated research scanner located near the University of Bergen campus to alleviate the burden on hospital facilities, advocating for increased prioritization of research over clinical use, and exploring possibilities for more favorable pricing structures. Furthermore, fostering a collaborative research environment, particularly in Tromsø, was seen as a valuable step in supporting and strengthening the MRI research community. The challenge of existing scanner upgrades at the University of Oslo was also noted, suggesting the need for careful coordination and resource allocation.

Conclusion

This survey has unequivocally demonstrated a significant and unmet need for dedicated research-focused MRI scanners across Norway. The strong consensus across various institutions and research roles highlights a critical bottleneck hindering scientific progress. Researchers consistently reported limitations in access, impacting study design, sample sizes, and ultimately, the quality and scope of their investigations. The potential for enhanced collaborations, multi-site studies, and innovation in MRI methodologies is clearly evident, but currently stifled by inadequate resources. This data serves as a compelling call to action, urging funding bodies, universities, and hospitals to prioritize investment in dedicated research MRI infrastructure. By addressing this crucial need, Norway can unlock its potential as a leader in cutting-edge neuroimaging research, driving advancements in our understanding of the brain, improving healthcare outcomes, and fostering a thriving scientific community. Failure to act will not only impede current research efforts but also jeopardize Norway’s future competitiveness in this rapidly evolving field.
